[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating dependency issues**\n\nI'm trying to figure out what happens if I have dependencies on Hazelcast 3 and 5. It seems like Hazelcast 5 doesn't have the old `com.hazelcast.core.IMap`, only `com.hazelcast.map.IMap`. If both versions are included, there could be duplicate packages. If I call `Class.forName`, it succeeds, but then which `IMap` do I test imports against? It might be better to replace Hazelcast 3 with Hazelcast 5 and adapt my test imports, but I need to make sure to retain coverage for specific lines as any changes could affect the overall results.\n\n**Considering classloader issues**\n\nI’m thinking that class initialization can only choose one path due to the `static final` keyword. I wonder if there’s a way to force a separate classloader. However, testing shouldn’t use reflection directly unless it’s through the public API. Loading `HazelcastIMapAdapter` in an isolated classloader with a different classpath could mean direct classloading, which might not be acceptable. I need to find a better method to avoid potential issues with class loading and reflection.\n\n**Considering coverage in build.gradle**\n\nI’m thinking that the final build should include high coverage, but does it need both elements? I wonder if I need to inspect the build.gradle dependencies to see what might be included. Maybe it’s necessary to read through the existing file from our changes to adapt accordingly. It feels like there’s something crucial in there that I don't want to overlook, so I'll take a closer look.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0f8b2de55a1680c70169f56efba9a881938cc41fdc4b901982\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp9W8Jc49WZgC1k40IgyMzufpG64uW7OFN0QXPDvv_7yypxffgkqdxpfNNZ_D3zdOl25gUiW4ehuopt7XFaDu0is7R_ZgLF5elNTWwyx4WXNFFcZQNVqLPr_3K2h95ZJ05uB8vYU-vFhnnLHFEdiYToDjNt8WMtnUcMgO9_ygv0kLCy2DB-f8ji2MbA_bjZU3F6ICdQ5Une7Dxwr9Yjw